\f2\fs32 Voltage in an electrical system is equivalent to pressure in a fluid system, and just as a pump generates fluid pressure, voltage must be generated somehow.  There are several methods to produce a voltage, including 
\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::4>
\f2\fs32 chemical reactions
\f0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::4>
\f2\fs32  (such as in batteries) and the 
\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::4>
\f2\fs32 photovoltaic effect
\f0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::4>
\f2\fs32  (as in solar cells); however, the most important method is 
\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\b\fs32 electromagnetic induction
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\fs32 .  Electromagnetic induction is the process where a changing magnetic field induces (creates) an electric voltage in a nearby conductor.   This phenomenon is the basis for generating electricity in devices like generators and transformers and it will be described in more detail in <xref ref="topic-faradays-law"/>.\
A voltage source (power supply) such as a battery or generator is connected to the attached circuit at two points called the 
\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\b\fs32 terminals
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\fs32 . The voltage between the terminals will drive current flow from the positive terminal to the negative terminal.  The term 
\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\b\fs32 polarity
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\fs32  in typically refers to the orientation of the terminals. In simple terms, it indicates which terminal is positive and which is negative with respect to some reference point.
\f0\fs24 <!$Scr_Ps::0>}